<subSubSection id="B505699231B6A29A70BAF564EC9FF3E3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph id="2E1EB59BB90195B9770A5DC958BD5985" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9554EC245B91FDAC41DA7B141977FE52" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Medium size. Colouration dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F6501DDEB7E157B3D1E31CB127B99000" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A male and female dorsal and lateral view of Gryllidae species. Subfamily Gryllinae: 1, 2 Acheta domesticus ♂ ♀, 3 A. hispanicus ♂, 4, 5 Gryllus (Gryllus) bimaculatus ♀ ♂, 6 G. (Gryllus) campestris ♀, 7 G. septentrionalis ♀, 8 Gryllodes sigillatus ♂ B male and female dorsal and lateral view of Gryllidae species. Subfamily Gryllinae: 9 Gryllodes supplicans ♀, 10 Teleogryllus (Brachyteleogryllus) occipitalis ♀, 11,12 T. (Brachyteleogryllus) commodus ♂ ♀, 13 Modicogryllus sindhensis sp. nov. ♀, 14 Svercus palmetorum ♀ C male and female dorsal and lateral view of Gryllidae species. Subfamily Gryllinae: 15 Miogryllus itaquiensis ♀, 16 Callogryllus saeedi ♀, 17 C. ovilongus ♀, 18 C. bilineatus ♀, 19 Lepidogryllus siamensis ♀, Subfamily Oecanthinae: 20 Oecanthus fultoni ♀. Abbreviations: D, dorsal, L, lateral. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.69850.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/623588" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1S</figureCitation>
). Head shiny brown, short, narrow, ocelli black, horizontal dark band between (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="3F7054E51110602CEA885EDAA51B712F" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Male and female head dorsal view of Gryllidae species, subfamily Gryllinae: 11 T. (Brachyteleogryllus) commodus ♀, 12 Modicogryllus sindhensis sp. nov. ♀, 13 Svercus palmetorum ♀, 14 Miogryllus itaquiensis ♀, 15 Callogryllus saeedi ♀, 16 C. ovilongus ♀, 17 C. bilineatus ♀, 18 Lepidogryllus siamensis ♀. Subfamily Oecanthinae: 19 Oecanthus fultoni ♀. Abbreviations: D, dorsal, L, lateral. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.69850.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/623590" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3H</figureCitation>
). Pronotum as long as head, 2 
<normalizedToken id="F7726C74991CBDD2E53F06C50B71E7FC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
wider than long on dorsal field, anterior and posterior margin pilose, truncated, dorsal surface brownish, mottled; lateral lobe of pronotum a little deeper than pronotal length (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A93790F91338EC84D184C7DCAB48D6C9" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Male and female pronotum dorsal view of Gryllidae species, subfamily Gryllinae: 11, 12 T. (Brachyteleogryllus) commodus ♂ ♀, 13 Modicogryllus sindhensis sp. nov. ♀, 14 Svercus palmetorum ♀, 15 Miogryllus itaquiensis ♀, 16 Callogryllus saeedi ♀, 17 C. ovilongus ♀, 18 C. bilineatus ♀, 19 Lepidogryllus siamensis ♀, Subfamily Oecanthinae: 20 Oecanthus fultoni ♀. Abbreviations: D, dorsal, L, lateral. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.69850.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/623592" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5I</figureCitation>
). Elytra hardly reaching abdominal end. Wings well developed, with condensed veins (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9D499C059A1C09654BBC070D34EC0F6F" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Male and female tegmen dorsal view of Gryllidae species, subfamily Gryllinae: 14 Svercus palmetorum ♀, 15 Miogryllus itaquiensis ♀, 16 Callogryllus saeedi ♀, 17 C. ovilongus ♀, 18 C. bilineatus ♀, 19 Lepidogryllus siamensis ♀, Subfamily Oecanthinae: 20 Oecanthus fultoni ♀. Abbreviations: D, dorsal, L, lateral. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.69850.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/623597" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10F</figureCitation>
). Legs brown, hind femora much longer than middle femora. Posterior tibia armed with seven external, three medio-internal spines, very wide at anterior, numerous patches on dorsal surface (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="47956A054AA1898AC9E9FE0A45BC2013" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Femur and tibia dorsal view of Gryllidae species, subfamily Gryllinae: 13 Svercus palmetorum ♀, 14 Miogryllus itaquiensis ♀, 15 Callogryllus saeedi ♀, 16 C. bilineatus ♀, 17 Lepidogryllus siamensis ♀, Subfamily Oecanthinae: 18 Oecanthus fultoni ♀. Abbreviations: D, dorsal, L, lateral. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.69850.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/623594" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7E</figureCitation>
). Abdomen brown. Cerci long tapered. Ovipositor long, straight, with yellowish base (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EEA55C73ABB479178E1D7610D7655C33" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A male and female dorsal and lateral view of Gryllidae species. Subfamily Gryllinae: 1, 2 Acheta domesticus ♂ ♀, 3 A. hispanicus ♂, 4, 5 Gryllus (Gryllus) bimaculatus ♀ ♂, 6 G. (Gryllus) campestris ♀, 7 G. septentrionalis ♀, 8 Gryllodes sigillatus ♂ B male and female dorsal and lateral view of Gryllidae species. Subfamily Gryllinae: 9 Gryllodes supplicans ♀, 10 Teleogryllus (Brachyteleogryllus) occipitalis ♀, 11,12 T. (Brachyteleogryllus) commodus ♂ ♀, 13 Modicogryllus sindhensis sp. nov. ♀, 14 Svercus palmetorum ♀ C male and female dorsal and lateral view of Gryllidae species. Subfamily Gryllinae: 15 Miogryllus itaquiensis ♀, 16 Callogryllus saeedi ♀, 17 C. ovilongus ♀, 18 C. bilineatus ♀, 19 Lepidogryllus siamensis ♀, Subfamily Oecanthinae: 20 Oecanthus fultoni ♀. Abbreviations: D, dorsal, L, lateral. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1078.69850.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/623588" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1S</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A0ECEBF8FA6D880F17084A539774351" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="1090C68A0B1C9938D74B2BC28299B8A6" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Female</emphasis>
: LH 1.96(mm), LP 2.03(mm), LT 9.5(mm), LF 5.6(mm), LT 07(mm), LT 04(mm), TBL 11(mm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="81667F9BEB1115C4CA16334169A39D26" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="BEB1D0CE979325F33354924A5D65EF4A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A92C146D953B7F459F5D00EEFA30D74D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species was recorded for the first time from the village Ramalani, Umerkot, on the roots of 
<taxonomicName id="ADBEF2A14A66A92C89DA50642812BD7D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acacia nilotia" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nilotia">
<emphasis id="0F7B53BC638048D1034E73390C7671BA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Acacia nilotia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
locally known as 
<normalizedToken id="4F66D676822281DC08285695CC1C139A" originalValue="“babul”">&quot;babul&quot;</normalizedToken>
. This is a medium-sized, thorny, nearly evergreen tree found in the desert area. Generally, it grows to 20-25 mm but may remain shrubby in poor conditions. Our specimen was collected from a shrub. This tree provides limber, fuel, shade, food, dye, and gum, and it also impacts the environment positively through soil reclamation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="866F4BE48F210B8B301FC895DF661FB7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C6C2A55EC08769E586CFC28C7022267F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Global distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="09F9F575C3A146DA3796C3D6DF488437" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Korea, Japan, Taiwan, Thailand, India, Hawaii, China, Pakistan (
<bibRefCitation id="41CEDAF8C0DBC5FACE93E5F5E354BFB2" author="Cigliano, MM" journalOrPublisher="The Zoological Survey of India, Calcutta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://Orthoptera.SpeciesFile.org" refId="B6" refString="Cigliano, MM, Braun, H, Eades, DC, Otte, D, 2020. Orthoptera species file online, version 5.0/5.0. http://Orthoptera.SpeciesFile.org" title="Orthoptera species file online, version 5.0 / 5.0." url="http://Orthoptera.SpeciesFile.org" year="2020">Cigliano et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0F92758B9038BBFD1969BBB02FCCD31F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="6AA66B9CE7BB2E39D4B72CB5F03D0617" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0E24A18D565F4D3734A60501075323DE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="4D65786CFFCF3885F8E899B12F1AE317" authorityName="Otte &amp; Alexander" authorityYear="1983" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Lepidogryllus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepidogryllus" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A8EE1B7A60A4817193A38F238402CB8F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Lepidogryllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very close morphological resemblance with 
<taxonomicName id="635413A2567096508046BC64D3613A9D" authorityName="Randell" authorityYear="1964" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Velarifictorus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Velarifictorus" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1A4D98000058E53AD4E77414A68B7D8D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Velarifictorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: the male has an enlarged round head with a swollen frons (Randell, 1964). 
<bibRefCitation id="E65B8FB96B958F50204F628DA28C8EE9" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5635/ASED.2013.29.4.294" author="Kim, TW" journalOrPublisher="Animal Systematics Evolution and Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="294 - 307" refId="B14" refString="Kim, TW, 2013. A Taxonomic Study on the Burrowing Cricket Genus Velarifictorus with morphologically resembled Genus Lepidogryllus (Orthoptera: Gryllidae: Gryllinae) in Korea. Animal Systematics Evolution and Diversity 29 (4): 294 - 307, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5635/ASED.2013.29.4.294" title="A Taxonomic Study on the Burrowing Cricket Genus Velarifictorus with morphologically resembled Genus Lepidogryllus (Orthoptera: Gryllidae: Gryllinae) in Korea." url="https://doi.org/10.5635/ASED.2013.29.4.294" volume="29" year="2013">Kim (2013)</bibRefCitation>
also reported the many similarities between these two genera. The species of these genera also have very significant variation in their morphometric parameters. 
<bibRefCitation id="3B1F35E3E0D4F3DA0F0F5941709B77B6" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5635/ASED.2013.29.4.294" author="Kim, TW" journalOrPublisher="Animal Systematics Evolution and Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="294 - 307" refId="B14" refString="Kim, TW, 2013. A Taxonomic Study on the Burrowing Cricket Genus Velarifictorus with morphologically resembled Genus Lepidogryllus (Orthoptera: Gryllidae: Gryllinae) in Korea. Animal Systematics Evolution and Diversity 29 (4): 294 - 307, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5635/ASED.2013.29.4.294" title="A Taxonomic Study on the Burrowing Cricket Genus Velarifictorus with morphologically resembled Genus Lepidogryllus (Orthoptera: Gryllidae: Gryllinae) in Korea." url="https://doi.org/10.5635/ASED.2013.29.4.294" volume="29" year="2013">Kim (2013)</bibRefCitation>
reported a body length of 14-15.2 mm in 
<taxonomicName id="09C183C8EA5CA8590773643BC9F9045D" genus="L." lsidName="L. siamensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="siamensis">
<emphasis id="F35C6EF1413A314045C00C79F5BAF29F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. siamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; we report a body length 11 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
